[1667.418947, "o", "SSH-COPY-ID(1)              BSD General Commands Manual             SSH-COPY-ID(1)\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mNAME\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n     \u001b[1mssh-copy-id\u001b[0m — use locally available keys to authorise logins on a remote ma‐\u001b[m\r\n     chine\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mSYNOPSIS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n     \u001b[1mssh-copy-id\u001b[0m [\u001b[1m-f\u001b[0m] [\u001b[1m-n\u001b[0m] [\u001b[1m-s\u001b[0m] [\u001b[1m-i\u001b[0m [\u001b[4midentity_file\u001b[24m]] [\u001b[1m-p\u001b[0m \u001b[4mport\u001b[24m] [\u001b[1m-o\u001b[0m \u001b[4mssh_option\u001b[24m]\u001b[m\r\n                 [\u001b[4muser\u001b[24m@]\u001b[4mhostname\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n     \u001b[1mssh-copy-id\u001b[0m \u001b[1m-h\u001b[0m | \u001b[1m-\u001b[0m?\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mDESCRIPTION\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n     \u001b[1mssh-copy-id\u001b[0m is a script that uses ssh(1) to log into a remote machine (pre‐\u001b[m\r\n     sumably using a login password, so password authentication should be enabled,\u001b[m\r\n     unless you've done some clever use of multiple identities).  It assembles a\u001b[m\r\n     list of one or more fingerprints (as described below) and tries to log in\u001b[m\r\n     with each key, to see if any of them are already installed (of course, if you\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page ssh-copy-id(1) line"]
[1667.418977, "o", " 1 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[1669.603794, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[KO\bO\u001b[KB\bB\r\u001b[K     are not using ssh-agent(1) this may result in you being repeatedly prompted\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page ssh-copy-id(1) line 2 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[1670.513192, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[KO\bO\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K\u001b[H\u001bMSSH-COPY-ID(1)              BSD General Commands Manual             SSH-COPY-ID(1)\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[18;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[7m Manual page ssh-copy-id(1) line 1 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[1670.637569, "o", "\r\u001b[K \u001b[KESC\b\b\bESC\u001b[KO\bO\u001b[KA\bA\r\u001b[K\u0007\r\u001b[K\u001b[7m Manual page ssh-copy-id(1) line 1 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[1706.766823, "o", "\r\u001b[K/"]
[1707.464578, "o", "\u001b[K-\b-"]
[1707.659208, "o", "\u001b[Ki\bi"]
[1708.139889, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[1708.14014, "o", "\u001b[1;1HSSH-COPY-ID(1)              BSD General Commands Manual             SSH-COPY-ID(1)\u001b[m"]
[1708.140167, "o", "\r\n"]
[1708.140177, "o", "\u001b[2;1H\u001b[m"]
[1708.140187, "o", "\r\n"]
[1708.140196, "o", "\u001b[3;1H\u001b[1mNAME\u001b[0m\u001b[m"]
[1708.14021, "o", "\r\n"]
[1708.140221, "o", "\u001b[4;1H     \u001b[1mssh-copy-id\u001b[0m — use locally available keys to authorise logins on a remote ma‐\u001b[m"]
[1708.140232, "o", "\r\n"]
[1708.140241, "o", "\u001b[5;1H     chine\u001b[m"]
[1708.14025, "o", "\r\n"]
[1708.14026, "o", "\u001b[6;1H\u001b[m"]
[1708.140269, "o", "\r\n"]
[1708.140279, "o", "\u001b[7;1H\u001b[1mSYNOPSIS\u001b[0m\u001b[m"]
[1708.140287, "o", "\r\n"]
[1708.140316, "o", "\u001b[8;1H     \u001b[1mssh-copy-id\u001b[0m [\u001b[1m-f\u001b[0m] [\u001b[1m-n\u001b[0m] [\u001b[1m-s\u001b[0m] [\u001b[1m-i\u001b[0m [\u001b[4midentity_file\u001b[24m]] [\u001b[1m-p\u001b[0m \u001b[4mport\u001b[24m] [\u001b[1m-o\u001b[0m \u001b[4mssh_option\u001b[24m]\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[9;1H                 [\u001b[4muser\u001b[24m@]\u001b[4mhostname\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[10;1H     \u001b[1mssh-copy-id\u001b[0m \u001b[1m-h\u001b[0m | \u001b[1m-\u001b[0m?\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[11;1H\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[12;1H\u001b[1mDESCRIPTION\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[13;1H     \u001b[1mssh-copy-id\u001b[0m is a script that uses ssh(1) to log into a remote machine (pre‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[14;1H     sumably using a login password, so password authentication should be enabled,\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[15;1H     unless you've done some clever use of multiple identities).  It assembles a\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[16;1H     list of one or more fingerprints (as described below) and tries to log in\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[17;1H     with each key, to see i"]
[1708.140544, "o", "f any of them are already installed (of course, if you\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[18;1H\u001b[1;1HSSH-COPY\u001b[7m-I\u001b[27mD(1)              BSD General Commands Manual             SSH-COPY\u001b[7m-I\u001b[27mD(1)\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[2;1H\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[3;1H\u001b[1mNAME\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[4;1H     \u001b[1mssh-copy\u001b[0m\u001b[1m\u001b[7m-i\u001b[27m\u001b[0m\u001b[1md\u001b[0m — use locally available keys to authorise logins on a remote ma‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[5;1H     chine\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[6;1H\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7;1H\u001b[1mSYNOPSIS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[8;1H     \u001b[1mssh-copy\u001b[0m\u001b[1m\u001b[7m-i\u001b[27m\u001b[0m\u001b[1md\u001b[0m [\u001b[1m-f\u001b[0m] [\u001b[1m-n\u001b[0m] [\u001b[1m-s\u001b[0m] [\u001b[1m\u001b[7m-i\u001b[27m\u001b[0m [\u001b[4midentity_file\u001b[24m]] [\u001b[1m-p\u001b[0m \u001b[4mport\u001b[24m] [\u001b[1m-o\u001b[0m \u001b[4mssh_option\u001b[24m]\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[9;1H                 [\u001b[4muser\u001b[24m@]\u001b[4mhostname\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[10;1H     \u001b[1mssh-copy\u001b[0m\u001b[1m\u001b[7m-i\u001b[27m\u001b[0m\u001b[1md\u001b[0m \u001b[1m-h\u001b[0m | \u001b[1m-\u001b[0m?\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[11;1H\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[12;1H\u001b[1mDESCRIPTION\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[13;1H     \u001b[1mssh-copy\u001b[0m\u001b[1m\u001b[7m-i\u001b[27m\u001b[0m\u001b[1md\u001b[0m is a script that uses ssh(1) to log into a remote machine (pre‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[14;1H     sumably using a login password, so password authentication should be enabled,\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[15;1H  "]
[1708.140556, "o", "   unless you'"]
[1708.14063, "o", "ve done some clever use of multiple identities).  It assembles a\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[16;1H     list of one or more fingerprints (as described below) and tries to log in\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[17;1H     with each key, to see if any of them are already installed (of course, if you\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[18;1H\r\u001b[K\u001b[7m Manual page ssh-copy-id(1) line 1 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[1708.919828, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[1708.919951, "o", "     are not using ssh-agent(1) this may result in you being repeatedly prompted\u001b[m\r\n     for pass-phrases).  It then assembles a list of those that failed to log in,\u001b[m\r\n     and using ssh, enables logins with those keys on the remote server.  By de‐\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page ssh-copy-id(1) line 4/115 18% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[1709.15115, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K     fault it adds the keys by appending them to the remote user's\u001b[m\r\n     \u001b[4m~/.ssh/authorized_keys\u001b[24m (creating the file, and directory, if necessary).  It\u001b[m\r\n     is also capable of detecting if the remote system is a NetScreen, and using\u001b[m\r\n     its ‘set ssh pka-dsa key ...’ command instead.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page ssh-copy-id(1) line 8/115 23% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[1709.309386, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[1709.309407, "o", "\u001b[m\r\n     The options are as follows:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page ssh-copy-id(1) line 10/115 23% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[1709.435955, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[1709.435991, "o", "\u001b[m\r\n     \u001b[1m\u001b[7m-i\u001b[27m\u001b[0m \u001b[4midentity_file\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n             Use only the key(s) contained in \u001b[4midentity_file\u001b[24m (rather than looking\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page ssh-copy-id(1) line 13/115 26% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[1709.571566, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[1709.571695, "o", "             for identities via ssh-add(1) or in the \u001b[1mdefault_ID_file\u001b[0m).  If the\u001b[m\r\n             filename does not end in \u001b[4m.pub\u001b[24m this is added.  If the filename is\u001b[m\r\n             omitted, the \u001b[1mdefault_ID_file\u001b[0m is used.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n             Note that this can be used to ensure that the keys copied have the\u001b[m\r\n             comment one prefers and/or extra options applied, by ensuring that\u001b[m\r\n             the key file has these set as preferred before the copy is attempted.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n     \u001b[1m-f\u001b[0m      Forced mode: doesn't check if the keys are present on the remote\u001b[m\r\n             server.  This means that it does not need the private key.  Of\u001b[m\r\n             course, this can result in more than one copy of the key being in‐\u001b[m\r\n             stalled on the remote system.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n     \u001b[1m-n\u001b[0m      do a dry-run.  Instead of installing keys on the remote system simply\u001b[m\r\n             prints the key(s) that would have been installed.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page ssh-copy-id(1) line 28/115 "]
[1709.571708, "o", "40% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[1709.698972, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[1709.699157, "o", "...skipping...\r\n     Default behaviour without \u001b[1m\u001b[7m-i\u001b[27m\u001b[0m, is to check if ‘ssh-add -L’ provides any out‐\u001b[m\r\n     put, and if so those keys are used.  Note that this results in the comment on\u001b[m\r\n     the key being the filename that was given to ssh-add(1) when the key was\u001b[m\r\n     loaded into your ssh-agent(1) rather than the comment contained in that file,\u001b[m\r\n     which is a bit of a shame.  Otherwise, if ssh-add(1) provides no keys con‐\u001b[m\r\n     tents of the \u001b[1mdefault_ID_file\u001b[0m will be used.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n     The \u001b[1mdefault_ID_file\u001b[0m is the most recent file that matches: \u001b[4m~/.ssh/id*.pub\u001b[24m,\u001b[m\r\n     (excluding those that match \u001b[4m~/.ssh/*-cert.pub\u001b[24m) so if you create a key that is\u001b[m\r\n     not the one you want \u001b[1mssh-copy\u001b[0m\u001b[1m\u001b[7m-i\u001b[27m\u001b[0m\u001b[1md\u001b[0m to use, just use touch(1) on your preferred\u001b[m\r\n     key's \u001b[4m.pub\u001b[24m file to reinstate it as the most recent.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mEXAMPLES\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n     If you have already installed keys from one system on a lot of remote hosts,\u001b"]
[1709.699172, "o", "[m\r\n     and you then create a new key, on a new client machine, say, it can be diffi‐\u001b[m\r\n     cult to keep track of which systems on which you've installed the new key.\u001b[m\r\n     One way of dealing with this is to load both the new key and old key(s) into\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page ssh-copy-id(1) line 63/115 72% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[1710.269847, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[1710.269878, "o", "     your ssh-agent(1).  Load the new key first, without the \u001b[1m-c\u001b[0m option, then load\u001b[m\r\n     one or more old keys into the agent, possibly by ssh\u001b[7m-i\u001b[27mng to the client ma‐\u001b[m\r\n     chine that has that old key, using the \u001b[1m-A\u001b[0m option to allow agent forwarding:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           user@newclient$ ssh-add\u001b[m\r\n           user@newclient$ ssh -A old.client\u001b[m\r\n           user@oldl$ ssh-add -c\u001b[m\r\n           ... prompt for pass-phrase ...\u001b[m\r\n           user@old$ logoff\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page ssh-copy-id(1) line 72/115 78% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[1710.51628, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[1710.51644, "o", "           user@newclient$ ssh someserver\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n     now, if the new key is installed on the server, you'll be allowed in un‐\u001b[m\r\n     prompted, whereas if you only have the old key(s) enabled, you'll be asked\u001b[m\r\n     for confirmation, which is your cue to log back out and run\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           user@newclient$ ssh-copy\u001b[7m-i\u001b[27md \u001b[7m-i\u001b[27m someserver\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n     The reason you might want to specify the \u001b[7m-i\u001b[27m option in this case is to ensure\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page ssh-copy-id(1) line 81/115 84% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[1710.854769, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K"]
[1710.85482, "o", "     that the comment on the installed key is the one from the \u001b[4m.pub\u001b[24m file, rather\u001b[m\r\n     than just the filename that was loaded into your agent.  It also ensures that\u001b[m\r\n     only the id you intended is installed, rather than all the keys that you have\u001b[m\r\n     in your ssh-agent(1).  Of course, you can specify another id, or use the con‐\u001b[m\r\n     tents of the ssh-agent(1) as you prefer.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n     Having mentioned ssh-add(1)'s \u001b[1m-c\u001b[0m option, you might consider using this when‐\u001b[m\r\n     ever using agent forwarding to avoid your key being hijacked, but it is much\u001b[m\r\n     better to instead use ssh(1)'s \u001b[4mProxyCommand\u001b[24m and \u001b[1m-W\u001b[0m option, to bounce through\u001b[m\r\n     remote servers while always doing direct end-to-end authentication. This way\u001b[m\r\n     the middle hop(s) don't get access to your ssh-agent(1).  A web search for\u001b[m\r\n     ‘ssh proxycommand nc’ should prove enlightening (N.B. the modern approach is\u001b[m\r\n     to use the \u001b[1m-W\u001b[0m option, rather than nc(1)).\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7"]
[1710.854824, "o", "m Manual page ssh-copy-id(1) line 95/115 98% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[1711.221951, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K\u001b[1mSEE\u001b[0m \u001b[1mALSO\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n     ssh(1), ssh-agent(1), sshd(8)\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page ssh-copy-id(1) line 97/115 99% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[1711.530032, "o", "\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K\r\u001b[K\u001b[7mPattern not found  (press RETURN)\u001b[27m"]
[1711.889411, "o", "\u001b[18;1H\u001b[K\r\u001b[K/\r\u001b[K\r\u001b[K\u001b[7mPattern not found  (press RETURN)\u001b[27m"]
